<DocsPageSubtitle>
    How reporting works
</DocsPageSubtitle>

<DocsPageParagraph>
    A report starts as a <Code Tag>Report</Code> component. In the simplest case, you declare the page, bands, and elements directly in Razor. Blazorise reads that declarative template and creates a report definition that can be rendered in preview mode or opened in design mode.
</DocsPageParagraph>

<DocsPageParagraph>
    The declarative model is intended to be the first step: it keeps the initial report close to the application UI, while still producing a structured definition that can later be saved, restored, edited, or generated from code.
</DocsPageParagraph>

<DocsPageSection>
    <DocsPageSectionHeader Title="Start declaratively">
        Use Razor markup to describe the report template. This example creates an invoice report with a page, bands, text, fields, and simple layout elements.
    </DocsPageSectionHeader>
    <DocsPageSectionContent Code="ReportingBasicInvoiceExample" Outlined FullWidth>
        <ReportingBasicInvoiceExample />
    </DocsPageSectionContent>
</DocsPageSection>

<DocsPageSubtitle>
    Where to go next
</DocsPageSubtitle>

<DocsPageParagraph>
    After the first report is rendering, build it up in layers. Each focused page goes deeper into one part of the reporting model.
</DocsPageParagraph>

<DocsPageParagraph>
    <UnorderedList>
        <UnorderedListItem>
            Start with <Anchor To="docs/extensions/reporting/layout">layout</Anchor> to understand pages, bands, report measurements, fields, lines, rectangles, and layout tables.
        </UnorderedListItem>
        <UnorderedListItem>
            Move to <Anchor To="docs/extensions/reporting/data-sources">data sources</Anchor> when the report needs object data, nested fields, and repeating detail bands.
        </UnorderedListItem>
        <UnorderedListItem>
            Use <Anchor To="docs/extensions/reporting/expressions">expressions</Anchor> for formula fields, calculated values, and running totals.
        </UnorderedListItem>
        <UnorderedListItem>
            Open <Anchor To="docs/extensions/reporting/designer">designer</Anchor> when users should edit the generated definition, manage panes, customize the toolbar, and persist report state.
        </UnorderedListItem>
        <UnorderedListItem>
            Finish with <Anchor To="docs/extensions/reporting/pdf-export">PDF export</Anchor> when the report definition should produce a downloadable file.
        </UnorderedListItem>
        <UnorderedListItem>
            Use the <Anchor To="docs/extensions/reporting/api">API reference</Anchor> when you need the full component and model surface.
        </UnorderedListItem>
    </UnorderedList>
</DocsPageParagraph>

<DocsPageSubtitle>
    From declarative to code-driven
</DocsPageSubtitle>

<DocsPageParagraph>
    The declarative template is only the initial source of the report definition. Once created, the same definition can be edited in the designer, bound to application state, saved, restored, or passed to services for preview and export.
</DocsPageParagraph>

<DocsPageParagraph>
    That progression is the main reporting workflow: describe the first version in Razor, let the designer modify the definition when needed, and use code for persistence, integration, and output generation.
</DocsPageParagraph>

